ns, and other individuals and institutions who invest in venture funds, who=
 will take that money, reinvest some into the next generation of venture fu=
nds, and operate their institutions with the rest.=C2=A0
Way back in 2007, before he became a VC himself, Marc Andreessen wrote [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/a46f8c71-c320-4607-9dc6-682a24088199?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
The best VCs get to improve society in two ways: by helping new companies t=
ake shape and contribute new technologies and medical cures into the world,=
 and by helping universities and foundations execute their missions to educ=
ate and improve people=E2=80=99s lives.
The world, for its part, may get AGI in the bargain.=C2=A0
It is not from the benevolence of the venture capitalist that we expect our=
 AGI, but from their regard to their own self interest.
The Visible Invisible Hand
The invisible hand is more visible in venture capital than it is in any oth=
er asset class.=C2=A0
Venture is an ecosystem made up of parties acting in their own self-interes=
t that seems to operate with some sort of collective intelligence on a long=
er timescale.=C2=A0
If you zoom in on the behavior of any one participant at any given time, yo=
u might think that they=E2=80=99re behaving stupidly. In many cases, they a=
re. The ecosystem works not in spite of, but because of, the stupidity of s=
ome of its participants.=C2=A0
Venture capitalists are willing to fund companies creating new technologies=
 even if those companies don=E2=80=99t seem to have a viable business model=
 in sight. The best venture capitalists try to fund companies that marry ne=
w technology with viable business models, but some technologies are just to=
o early to make any economic sense. That=E2=80=99s OK! There are venture ca=
pitalists willing to fund those, too.=C2=A0
Maybe they believe that the team is smart and will figure out a model. Mayb=
e they hope the company will be acquired for its technology. Maybe they hop=
e the market will catch up while the company is still a going concern. Mayb=
e they just got really excited and bought into the hype.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s easy to make fun of VCs for buying into hype so quickly. My X =
feed is chock full of memes about VCs who went from being web3 investors to=
 AI investors to Gundo investors faster than you can say =E2=80=9CPatagonia=
 vest.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I think hype-buying is one of venture capitalists=E2=80=99 most endearing q=
ualities.=C2=A0
Hype is usually an indicator that there=E2=80=99s something there, even if =
that something is a long ways away. As I wrote in Capitalism Onchained [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/e659e1e7-fcb7-4139-82dc-7a344cf167f8?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CAny te=
chnology that is sufficiently valuable in its ideal state will eventually r=
each that ideal state.=E2=80=9D But it takes years, sometimes decades, of w=
inding experimentation [ https://substack.com/redirect/ae0918ea-39ac-424c-b=
c10-2b4f0b0bc0f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ], and millions, sometimes billions, of dollars to reach that stat=
e, or even to reach a pre-ideal state in which the technology can be built =
and sold profitably.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Who=E2=80=99s going to fund that experimentation period? A bank? The public=
 markets? Nope. Venture capitalists.=C2=A0
Take the clean tech bubble that Kleiner Perkins helped kick off in the mid-=
2000s. In 2007, Kleiner Perkins Partner John Doerr said [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/ed97fee5-34ee-458c-b840-04105d1d56cf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CGoing green is bigger=
 than the Internet. It could be the biggest economic opportunity of the 21s=
t century.=E2=80=9D
Kleiner and other venture capitalists ended up investing a tremendous amoun=
t of money investing in clean tech =E2=80=93 on the order of tens of billio=
ns of dollars. They lost money on the vast majority of those investments. B=
ut their investment attracted talent to the industry and provided an incent=
ive to improve clean technologies that helped lay the groundwork for the dr=
amatic increase in renewable and storage capacity we=E2=80=99re benefiting =
from today, nearly two decades later.=C2=A0And Tesla, which at a $626 billi=
on market cap is worth multiples of all of the money invested in clean tech=
=2E=20
Along with the government, which funds basic research, venture capitalists =
often fund too-early technologies as they take their first steps out of the=
 lab and into the cutthroat world of the market. They provide the capital t=
hat sustains technologies through the flat-looking parts of eventually expo=
nential curves [ https://substack.com/redirect/c5db5436-5cb7-406b-8ebb-e5aa=
1ef1d08c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ], and often lose that capital. Then, when the curves go exponential, the =
next generation of venture capitalists take advantage to make investments t=
hat actually deliver returns.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s what I mean when I say that there seems to be collective int=
elligence at play on longer timescales. The opportunity to generate returns=
 today might not exist if someone hadn=E2=80=99t been willing to lose money=
 decades ago. No venture capitalist does this altruistically =E2=80=93 they=
=E2=80=99re driven by the small, against-all-odds chance that this too-earl=
y technology might be the next big thing =E2=80=93 but in their mistakes th=
ey create opportunity for others.=C2=A0
Losing money is all fun and games for VCs because it=E2=80=99s not their mo=
ney, right?=20
But What About the Pensioners?=C2=A0
Whenever a specific investment goes south, a cry goes up for the poor pensi=
oners, charities, and endowments who are really the ones funding all of the=
se experiments behind the scenes.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m here to tell you that those pensioners are doing just fine, tha=
nk you very much.=C2=A0
Limited Partners (LPs) often manage large pools of capital that they invest=
 across a number of asset classes. Yale=E2=80=99s endowment, for example, i=
s roughly $42 billion.=C2=A0
NACUBO (The National Association of College and University Business Officer=
s) does an annual survey on endowments=E2=80=99 asset allocations. When Mar=
c Andreessen wrote The Truth About Venture Capitalists [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/059dadf9-9a49-4ee4-9855-59a05cdb8d95?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in 2007, NACUBO found that endow=
ments allocated 3.5% of their assets to venture capital. In 2023, that numb=
er grew to 11.9%.=C2=A0
LPs build portfolios that are diversified across asset classes, and then fu=
rther diversified within asset classes. Within venture, they will invest in=
 a number of funds, each with its own strategy: some early stage, some late=
 stage; some generalist, some vertical. They continue to invest across vint=
ages, meaning that every year, they=E2=80=99ll invest in new funds or re-in=
vest in funds they=E2=80=99ve already invested in. Those funds, in turn, di=
versify across a number of investments that fit their criteria over a numbe=
r of years.=C2=A0
From the LPs=E2=80=99 perspective, venture capital is a small but growing h=
igh-risk / high-reward piece of a much larger portfolio. If any individual =
investment that one (or multiple) of their venture managers make fails, no =
matter how spectacularly, it=E2=80=99s unlikely to have a big impact on the=
 overall portfolio. What=E2=80=99s more important to LPs is that venture as=
 an ecosystem continues to take the kinds of risks that have a shot at driv=
ing higher returns.=C2=A0
If one venture firm makes a bunch of too-early investments that lose a lot =
of money, that firm may go out of business, but the LP will still be around=
 when the fruits of those too-early technologies ripen.=20
From their gods-eye perspective, LPs can invest in all of the messiness =E2=
=80=93 the successes and the failures =E2=80=93 and expect that on the othe=
r side, in ten or so years, they=E2=80=99ll get multiples of their money ba=
ck.=C2=A0Then they=E2=80=99ll keep investing, and harvest the seeds sown by=
 the previous generation=E2=80=99s losers.=20
More returns means more money to donate to charity, fund growing pensions, =
run universities, and continue to invest in venture capital.=20
The Fund Size Paradox
One of the things LPs do with those returns is continue to invest in the fu=
nds that got them there, inflating those funds=E2=80=99 assets under manage=
ment over time.=20
The rise of the resulting megafunds has drawn criticism, occasionally from =
venture capitalists themselves [ https://substack.com/redirect/2049c02d-ef9=
a-4ac9-a682-01a6af5639e1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], based on the argument that large funds are terrible for=
 returns and exist to generate management fees.=C2=A0
Venture capital funds typically earn =E2=80=9C2 and 20=E2=80=9D: 2% managem=
ent fees and 20% carry. They take 2% of the fund size every year for ten ye=
ars to pay salaries and generally manage the fund, and they keep 20% of wha=
t they earn once they=E2=80=99ve paid back LPs.=C2=A0
The thinking behind the criticism of megafunds goes something like this: it=
=E2=80=99s harder to generate outsized returns on larger pools of capital t=
han it is on smaller pools of capital. Owning 20% of a company that IPOs fo=
r $10 billion means a 20x for a $100 million fund, but doesn=E2=80=99t even=
 return a $3 billion fund! But they don=E2=80=99t care, because they make 2=
% of a big number every year no matter what.=C2=A0
So if megafunds exist solely to milk fees out of LPs, why the hell do LPs d=
efinitionally invest more money in these larger funds than they do in small=
er funds?=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s go back to this graphic:
Assume that every year, there=E2=80=99s a certain amount of money that=E2=
=80=99s going to get allocated to venture capital and a certain number of c=
ompanies that are going to generate returns.=C2=A0
If all of the money that=E2=80=99s currently allocated to megafunds instead=
 got allocated to smaller early stage funds, there would be a few issues.=
=C2=A0
First, those small funds=E2=80=99 extraordinary returns would decrease. Mor=
e competition at the early stages would likely drive higher valuations and =
it would mean that each early stage fund would win fewer deals, decreasing =
the likelihood that they=E2=80=99ll own one of the handful of companies tha=
t matter.=C2=A0
Second, and more importantly, there would be less capital available downstr=
eam to fund winners. Some companies need hundreds of millions of dollars to=
 get to the point at which they can become profitable. This was somehow tru=
e of pure software companies, and it will be increasingly true as venture c=
apital funds more capital intensive foundation model and deep tech companie=
s.=C2=A0
Without megafunds operating at the Series A and beyond, more companies woul=
d fail before they have the chance to go public, which would lower overall =
returns to LPs. That, in turn, would mean that small, early stage funds cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t take the types of risks they need to take to generate those o=
utsized returns and give the wildest ideas a chance.=C2=A0
If anything, we need more megafunds. I recently spoke to one of my LPs who=
=E2=80=99s interested in deep tech investing in India, and his biggest conc=
ern isn=E2=80=99t the talent in the space (there=E2=80=99s a lot) or the ma=
rket (which is growing), but the lack of downstream capital. If even the mo=
st promising companies can=E2=80=99t raise the capital they need, then it=
=E2=80=99s really hard to justify starting or investing in a new company.=
=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s that invisible hand making itself visible again: self-inter=
ested parties dynamically evolving into an ecosystem with a robust capital =
pipeline. Larger firms are rewarded for playing their role in fees, smaller=
 firms are rewarded for playing theirs in higher upside when they=E2=80=99r=
e right. One is not better than the other; both are necessary.=C2=A0
Founders win, LPs win, and the world wins.
If megafunds win too by generating a lot of fees in the process, great! If =
you believe that megafunds earn too much money relative to the service they=
 provide, make like Jeff Bezos, treat their margin as your opportunity, and=
 go start a larger fund with lower fees or something.=C2=A0
An Aside on Fees
Speaking of megafund management fees, I think they=E2=80=99re among the mos=
t interesting buckets of capital in the world, and that we=E2=80=99ll see t=
hem utilized in increasingly beneficial ways.=C2=A0
The rationale is simple: if megafunds are confident that they=E2=80=99ll be=
