Founders can walk into a VC=E2=80=99s office with an idea and a dream, and =
leave with millions of dollars. They=E2=80=99ll hire people and build thing=
s that have ever only existed in their imagination. Most of them will fail,=
 and many of those who do will be able to walk back into those same offices=
 and get a fresh bag of money to try again. Some will succeed, and they=E2=
=80=99ll succeed so outrageously that the value they create will pay for al=
l of the failures and then some.=C2=A0They might even Make the World a Bett=
er Place=E2=84=A2=EF=B8=8F in the process.
I=E2=80=99d argue that even if venture capital underperformed other asset c=
lasses, generated 0% returns or something, it would be a net benefit to soc=
iety to have a pool of capital that funds crazy experimentation. But this i=
s capitalism, and returns are what keeps the machine humming. So the fact t=
hat VC has generated such strong returns over a long time horizon is key.=
=C2=A0
The question is: will venture continue to deliver returns?=C2=A0
I think the answer is undoubtedly, unquestionably yes.=C2=A0
Tech is Going to Get Much Bigger [ https://substack.com/redirect/552dcdb6-7=
02f-4c2c-bf8a-c14a010a1573?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] as tech=E2=80=99s total addressable market expands to =
include large existing industries that have been relatively untouched by te=
chnology, including industrials and agriculture. Cheaper energy, intelligen=
ce, and dexterity, in the words of Valar Atomics=E2=80=99 Isaiah Taylor [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/71262f7b-1d9a-4a7e-b118-e3484fa3fc7b?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], will mean new =
opportunities to attack old industries with cheaper, better products. Highe=
r margins in large industries will make for very valuable companies. And th=
ings that were previously impossible are becoming possible at an accelerate=
d rate.=C2=A0
Venture was created for times like this, when big shifts in underlying tech=
nologies create opportunities for crazy geniuses to build products that mig=
ht change the world.=C2=A0
If anything, the past few of decades of pure software investing were a nece=
ssary interstitial period during which bits developed to the point at which=
 they could make a meaningful impact on the world of atoms, and the next fe=
w will be the period during which the combination of bits and atoms made th=
e world a magical place.=C2=A0
The speed at which change will happen, the amount of capital these companie=
s will require, and the outlandish ambition of the projects founders will t=
ackle will mean more and bigger blowups than ever before, but it will also =
mean more and bigger winners. In the process, the world will get a suite of=
 new capabilities =E2=80=93 medicines, machines, money, (literal) moonshots=
 and more =E2=80=93 practically for free.=C2=A0
So by all means, ape into the Gundo! Fuel that techno-optimism! Lose many, =
and win some. The only mistake is to play it too safe, to fund things that =
don=E2=80=99t matter.=20
As tech gets much bigger, venture capital will get much bigger, too. That=
=E2=80=99s a beautiful thing.=C2=A0God bless the United States of America, =
and God bless venture capital =F0=9F=87=BA=F0=9F=87=B8
