 style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Along with the government, which funds basic research=
, venture capitalists often fund too-early technologies as they take their =
first steps out of the lab and into the cutthroat world of the market. They=
 provide the capital that sustains technologies through the flat-looking pa=
rts of eventually </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/c5db5436-=
5cb7-406b-8ebb-e5aa1ef1d08c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: =
underline;">exponential curves</a><span>, and often lose that capital. Then=
, when the curves go exponential, the next generation of venture capitalist=
s take advantage to make investments that actually deliver returns.&#160;</=
span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s what I mean when I say that there s=
eems to be collective intelligence at play on longer timescales. The opport=
unity to generate returns today might not exist if someone hadn&#8217;t bee=
n willing to lose money decades ago. No venture capitalist does this altrui=
stically &#8211; they&#8217;re driven by the small, against-all-odds chance=
 that this too-early technology might be the next big thing &#8211; but in =
their mistakes they create opportunity for others.&#160;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;">Losing money is all fun and games for VCs because it&#8217;s not their m=
oney, right? </p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appe=
arance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-a=
