ioners?</strong><span>&#160;</span></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Whenever a specif=
ic investment goes south, a cry goes up for the poor pensioners, charities,=
 and endowments who are really the ones funding all of these experiments be=
hind the scenes.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I&#8217;m here to tell you that=
 those pensioners are doing just fine, thank you very much.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">Limited Partners (LPs) often manage large pools of capital that=
 they invest across a number of asset classes. Yale&#8217;s endowment, for =
example, is roughly $42 billion.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>NACUBO (T=
he National Association of College and University Business Officers) does a=
n annual survey on endowments&#8217; asset allocations. When Marc Andreesse=
